🤖 Naive Bayes Classification (Gaussian, Bernoulli, Multinomial)

This project demonstrates the implementation of Naive Bayes classification algorithms using Python.

The objective is to understand how different Naive Bayes variants perform under different preprocessing conditions.

🛠️ Libraries Used
Python
NumPy
Pandas
Scikit-learn
📂 Dataset Description

The dataset contains:

Age
Estimated Salary
Purchased (Target Variable)

Features used:

Age
Estimated Salary

Target:

Purchased (0 or 1)
🔍 Project Workflow
1️⃣ Data Loading & Preparation
Loaded dataset using Pandas
Selected features (Age, Salary) as X
Selected Purchased as y
Split dataset into 80% training and 20% testing
🤖 Models Implemented
🔹 1. Gaussian Naive Bayes
No feature scaling required
Suitable for continuous data

Results:

Accuracy ≈ 92.5%

Confusion Matrix:

[[56  2]
 [ 4 18]]
🔹 2. Bernoulli Naive Bayes
Applied StandardScaler
Converted features into binary format

Results:

Evaluated using accuracy and confusion matrix
🔹 3. Multinomial Naive Bayes
Applied MinMaxScaler to ensure all values are positive
Suitable for count-based or positive data

Results:

Accuracy ≈ 72.5%

Confusion Matrix:

[[58  0]
 [22  0]]
📊 Model Evaluation

Each model was evaluated using:

Accuracy Score
Confusion Matrix
🎯 What I Learned
Differences between Gaussian, Bernoulli, and Multinomial Naive Bayes
Importance of choosing the correct model based on data type
Role of preprocessing in improving model performance
How Naive Bayes assumes feature independence

This project helped strengthen my understanding of probability-based classification algorithms.
